# Project Charter — Prompt Injection Attack & Defense Lab

## Project Summary
Build a controlled RAG chatbot environment to demonstrate, analyze, and defend against prompt
injection attacks. Deliverable: a reproducible lab with documented attack attempts, measured
defense effectiveness, and a final written report.

## Scope
**In scope:**
- Local RAG pipeline with a synthetic/public-domain document knowledge base
- Three attack categories: direct injection, data exfiltration, indirect (document) injection
- Two or more defensive techniques with measurable evaluation metrics

**Out of scope:**
- Any external or production systems
- Social engineering or attacks on real users

## Rules of Engagement (ROE)
- All testing is authorized-only; the only system under test is our own locally deployed instance
- No API keys, credentials, or private data will be embedded in the repo or knowledge base
- Attack payloads will be clearly labeled and isolated in the `/evidence` folder
- Project artifacts will not be used outside the academic context of CS381

## Methodology
1. **Environment setup** — Deploy RAG stack, ingest document corpus, verify baseline behavior
2. **Attack phase** — Craft and execute injection payloads; log raw outputs as evidence
3. **Defense phase** — Implement countermeasures; re-run identical payloads
4. **Evaluation** — Compute refusal rate and leakage metrics before vs. after defenses
5. **Report** — Document findings, limitations, and recommendations

## Milestones
| Week | Deliverable |
|---|---|
| Week 1 | Checkpoint 1: repo structure, README, charter (this document) |
| Week 2 | RAG environment running; baseline attack suite drafted |
| Week 3 | All attack categories executed and evidenced; defenses implemented |
| Week 4 | Evaluation complete; final report drafted and submitted |

## Success Criteria
- Refusal rate on injection payloads improves by ≥ 50% after defenses are applied
- Zero unintended data leakage from the knowledge base after defenses
- All three attack categories demonstrated with reproducible evidence
- Final report clearly explains each attack vector and the corresponding mitigation

## Ethics & Safety Statement
This project is conducted solely for educational purposes within the scope of CS381. All
experiments run against systems under our direct control. No external parties, production
services, or real user data are involved at any stage. Attack artifacts are stored only in this
private/public academic repository and will not be repurposed outside this course.
